{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52def980-fa21-44fe-8daa-d14805d3f50d","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract the file system behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n1. **Define an interface** like `IFileSystem` with methods matching what you use (`WriteAllText`, `ReadAllText`, `DirectoryExists`).\n2. **Create a real implementation** that delegates to `System.IO.File`/`Directory`.\n3. **Inject the interface** into classes that need file I/O.\n4. **Mock it in tests** using Moq, NSubstitute, or a simple fake.\n\nAlternatively, use the existing **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` out of the box plus an in-memory mock (`MockFileSystem`) for testing, saving you from writing your own wrappers.\n\n```csharp\n// With System.IO.Abstractions:\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public void Save(string path, string content)\n        => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n}\n\n// In tests:\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nsvc.Save(\"/tmp/test.txt\", \"hello\");\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/test.txt\"));\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e984ad27-e252-4450-afca-bd4f1de2acf7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a design/architecture question about abstracting file system dependencies for testability. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":379,"requestId":"5C2B:800AA:1FB5553:245F192:69F558A7"},"id":"6a51ed13-2bc4-40df-8197-85db57c9ad81","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:51:43.737Z","parentId":"99555c34-4781-4189-9727-f3aacb739bda"}
